		<p>
		<h3 class="piece_header"> Queer — It’s Not Just Sexual Orientation or Gender Identity </h3>		

People who meet me usually get the impression that I’m a pretty conventional guy. <br> <br>
I mean to say that I blend into a crowd. I’m a good listener, but if you get me going, I’m a good story teller too. I’m not loud, though.<br> <br>
I’m not flamboyant. My tastes are fairly conservative, even if I’m not conservative, not essentially. I’m always open to being different and unconventional.<br> <br>
I’m queer, and not just in the sense that I have a minority sexual orientation.<br> <br>
I’ve never had a relationship, not even my 10-year de facto marriage, that was sexually exclusive. I’ve never been interested in trying to duplicate or ape heterosexual, cisgender institutions and value systems.<br> <br>

Being queer — to me — means having the freedom to explore and invent ways of being, to create family, to live fully, to live differently from convention. <br> <br>

<strong> Let me tell you a story that helps explain what I mean. </strong> <br> <br>
I once had a friend with a beautiful summer house perched above a pristine lake in the Laurentian mountains.<br> <br>
He invited my boyfriend and me up quite often. We’d sit on the back porch at night wrapped in blankets, listening to gorgeous music floating across the lake from a nearby religious retreat.<br> <br>
We'd sip wine. We'd skinny dip in icy mountain runoff — skin stinging, gasping for breath.<br> <br>
During the day, we'd glide in a canoe through vast swathes of lily pads, fingers trilling through transparent water as we gazed at lazy frogs and eyed beavers bustling about their engineering marvels.<br> <br>

I’d dive for handful after handful of the chalky mussels that coated the rocky floor of a nearby cove. I’d steam them with white wine and lots of garlic and butter.<br> <br>
We’d swelter during the day, assaulted by a close, beating sun. The nights turned black and frigid the instant the swollen red disk sank below the lake’s edge— typical of the northerly clime.<br> <br>
One weekend, a friend joined us, seeking an escape from the hustle and bustle of life in the big city.
<br> <br>

Our little retreat enchanted him.<br> <br>
He swam, paddled, dove, and feasted on my cooking.<br> <br>
The second evening was particularly cold. He was shivering and joined my boyfriend and me under a thick quilt. Whether it was the magic of the moment, the beauty of the mountain vistas, or just the intimacy inspired by shared happiness, the three of us spent the night together, in the metaphorical sense.<br> <br>
How did it feel?<br> <br>
Sweet and good. Casual and not too significant. It felt like the pleasure of our holiday getaway was expanding and enveloping us like a warm cocoon.<br> <br>
We never had sex with our friend again, it never seemed like the thing to do.<br> <br> <br>

None of us ever regretted that night.<br> <br>
Frankly, none of us ever felt the need to seriously discuss it. We continued going out together sometimes. Our friend continued to come over for dinner every week or two.<br> <br>
We didn’t need to meet conventional sexual or romantic expections, so the fact of not meeting them just never seemed significant.<br> <br>
That’s what I mean by unconventional. That’s partly what I mean by queer, when I talk about queer.<br> <br>
I could tell other, similar stories, but this one seems apt.<br> <br>
I like it.
		</p>
	</div>

	<div class="piece_of_work" id="piece_one">
