		<h3 class="piece_header"> The Odd Couple — Mental Disability and Power Imbalance </h3>		
		<p>
Every once in a while I encounter something that rocks me a little, shakes up my presuppositions. <br> <br> 

When I was a teenager and young adult, people were first beginning to talk about the toxicity of power differential in relationships and marriages. I’m in my fifties. In the generations before mine, nobody would have understood the problem with differences in power. Men were the heads of family. Wives were perhaps not exactly subordinate, but they were not equal to their husbands. <br> <br> 

They weren’t supposed to be. <br> <br> 

Powerful men courted and wed their secretaries and other female assistants at work. It was a thing. Some women went to work to find men to marry. Tenured university professors had flings with or courted younger women students all the time. <br> <br> 

In some ways, these practices were even celebrated as romantic ideals. <br> <br> 

If you’re a lot younger than I am, you’re probably scratching your head right now. I can just hear you. Seriously? Ideal? Doesn’t everyone know that relationships need to be built on equality? <br> <br> 

Yes, we know that now. I was actually around to witness that sort of understanding take root. I’ve also witnessed the good the understanding has caused. A lot fewer people, especially young women, are subject to being manipulated and taken advantage of by men. <br> <br> 

Fewer young people are having their lives disrupted or ruined by more powerful older people using them and abusing them. Understanding the toxicity of unequal power has done a lot of good for a lot of folks. No question. <br> <br>

I’m glad for this new understanding of ours. <br> <br> 

Every once in a while, I see something that shakes me, though. Let me tell you a story. <br> <br> 

I knew Larry and Jim ages ago. <br> <br> <br>

Larry was perhaps forty when I first met them. Jim 30. They were both handsome, well dressed, fit but not gym-bunny fit. <br> <br> 

They were waltzing, two-stepping, and fox trotting at the synagogue social when I first spotted them. Jim’s inky hair was trimmed into tight ringlets. His full beard was not fashionable for the time, so he stood out. Drew my eye. <br> <br> 

Larry’s auburn locks were longer and beginning to thin. They whispered something about feminine values. <br> <br> 

Larry and Jim were a striking couple, like gems in a brooch that should have clashed, but ended up complementing one another. Something was odd about Jim, though. I couldn’t put my finger on it. <br> <br> 

At first. <br> <br> 

They were obviously in love. The way they looked at each other. The way Jim wouldn’t let himself be more than a few feet from Larry.
 <br> <br> 
I asked Lenny about them as we were browsing the buffet. I pointed with my chin. “You know those guys?”
 <br> <br> 
“Yeah. Larry? He’s a bookkeeper up at Random House. Good guy. Boring guy. You want I should introduce you later?”
 <br> <br> 
“I mean sure, I guess. I was just curious. That guy he’s with? What’s the deal?”
 <br> <br> 
“Oh, Jim? Larry’s Jim. Sweetest thing I ever saw.”
 <br> <br> 
Lenny’s pale blue eyes softened. He glanced over at Larry just as Jim was feeding him a piece of pastrami sandwich and laughing like a little kid.
 <br> <br> 
It finally clicked.
 <br> <br> 
“Lenny!” I gasped. “Jim isn’t, I mean Jim is … He’s not…”
 <br> <br> 
Lenny looked me in the eye and said the words very plainly, as he always did. “Yeah. He’s retarded. Slow… Really, really slow.”
 <br> <br> 
“But they were kissing!” I was shocked.
 <br> <br> 
“Because they’re lovers,” Lenny said softly, taking my hand. “They’ve loved each other for almost ten years. They live together.”
 <br> <br> 
It took me a while to process. I slowly got to know the two. Not well, really. I saw them maybe once a month over the next several years. We had them over to dinner a few times.
 <br> <br> 
I learned that Jim was pretty severely mentally disabled. He could mostly take care of himself, but he wasn’t capable of living on his own. I don’t know exactly what the issue was. What the diagnosis was.
 <br> <br> 
I know that some people whispered that Larry took advantage of Jim. Lenny had known them since they met, and he assured me that those accusations were baseless.
 <br> <br> 
The more I came to know the two, the more I saw that Lenny was right. They were incredibly patient with each other. They were incredibly tolerant of each other. They were absolutely devoted to each other.
 <br> <br> 
The last I heard they were growing old together, still together.
 <br> <br> 
If I had not come to know Larry and Jim, I think I would believe that a relationship like that could not work, that it might have to be abusive or exploitative by definition. The inherent power differential had to make the relationship impossible.
 <br> <br> 
But I did meet them. I did know them.
 <br> <br> 
And I know that each would be incredibly poorer without the other.
 <br> <br><br>
Don’t mistake the purpose of this story, please. I’m not suggesting that we ought to go back to the days when unequal relationships were expected and idealized. I’m just saying that sometimes we need to dig a little below the surface before we can understand the ground we’re walking on.
 <br> <br> 
Sometimes our presuppositions can do with a little good challenging.
		</p>
	</div>

	<div class="piece_of_work" id="piece_two">
