		<h3 class="piece_header"> Queer in Iran </h3>		
		<p>
		<strong> Hope under the Motor City stars </strong> <br> <br>

I was relaxing in the garden at Motor City Wine in Detroit’s Corktown last summer, sipping cool rosé with some friends. <br> <br>

The garden is a lovely spot on a hot summer’s evening. Leafy, breezy, cool. A cool crowd too. The hipster quotient is low, but the hip factor is high, if you take my meaning. <br> <br>

My friends and I were evidently showing the signs of the bottles we’d cracked open, because some young people approached us explaining that we were all loud enough that they’d heard us speaking French. <br> <br>

Would we mind if they sat down and chatted for a while? <br> <br>

It turns out they were young, urban Iranians who wanted to practice their own French, which turned out to be pretty good. <br> <br>

They were all university students or just a little older. Out of the five of them, three guys and two women, one of them was gay. All of them were very progressive, very irreligious, and would look at home in most of the world’s major cities. <br> <br>

I asked the gay guy something. “So, how’s life in Tehran? Are you free to be who you are? Like you and your friends are being tonight?” <br> <br>

“Sure,” he told me. “We have our friends, our places to go, our circles. Life is fine. In Tehran.” <br> <br>

“Meaning?” <br> <br>

“Lots of people in Iran are religious and conservative. If you live an urban lifestyle, and if you don’t do stupid things, you don’t have to live in the same world as those people. You can be you.” <br> <br>

We drank some more wine, offering glasses to our young guests, then said our goodbyes as they ran off to party and we prepared to call it a night. <br> <br>

I thought back to my own youth. I thought about my career in the Air Force. It occurred to me that I could have once said exactly what that young Iranian man had said to me. <br> <br>

I thought about all the incredible progress I’ve seen in my own lifetime, progress I could never have predicted and certainly didn’t expect. <br> <br>

Our table empty, I picked up the last bottle of wine. I tilted it, spilling the few remaining drops into my glass, which I raised in salute to the stars. I drank a silent toast of hope to the all queer people around the world still forced to live in darkness. <br> <br> <br>

I recently published a piece on Medium about my own lifetime of experiences related to queer acceptance. I think it might illustrate my thinking nicely with respect to the story above.
		</p>
	</div>


	<div class="piece_of_work" id="piece_three">
		<h1 onclick='show_default("piece_three")' class="go_back_btn">
