		<h3 class="piece_header"> Let’s Talk About HIV and AIDS </h3>		
		<p>
		<strong> What’s the deal with mothers passing the virus on to newborns? </strong> <br> <br>
Worldwide, the HIV epidemic is in decline. In much of the developed world, the virus has become rare, even among traditionally high-risk populations. Gay male populations in the United States and Canada, for example, are now seeing rates of new infections so low that HIV can no longer be considered endemic.
<br> <br>
Even in the world’s hardest-hit regions, like southern and eastern Africa, rates of new infections are finally beginning to decline instead of increase.
<br> <br>
We are not, however, living in a post-HIV world. Not yet.
<br> <br>
In future articles, I’ll be writing more on the end of the epidemic and public health strategies for reaching the elusive post-HIV state. Today, though, I’d like to concentrate on a facet of HIV disease that few people know much about — mother-to-child transmission and how to prevent it.
<br> <br>
First, some background.
<br> <br>
AIDS is the name of a syndrome of illnesses that can occur during the end stages of chronic, untreated infection with HIV, the Human Immunodeficiency Virus.
<br> <br>
People in treatment for HIV almost always see their viral levels reduced to undetectable. Their immune systems remain healthy. They don’t become ill. According to the US CDC, people living with HIV who are in effective treatment are unable to infect others sexually.
<br> <br>
Positive and and negative partners in sero-discordant couples have sex all the time without condoms and without pre-exposure prophylaxis medication — without any significant risk to the negative partner.
<br> <br>
While this surprises some people, it’s a relatively well-known phenomenon, especially among people living with HIV.
<br> <br>
What fewer people are aware of is that HIV-positive women can and do give birth to children with little to no risk, under proper medical care and supervision. Let me tell you about the latest medical news on that front.
<br> <br>
Women living with HIV, whether or not they have AIDS, can pass the virus on to their children in three ways. Let me detail those three ways and talk about how to prevent or mitigate risk in each circumstance.
<br> <br>
<strong> 1. During pregnancy. The virus can pass the placental barrier and infect the unborn child in utero. </strong>
<br> <br>
    - Mothers who start antiretroviral therapy (ART) before pregnancy, and who attain an undetectable viral load, can reduce the odds of in-utero transmission to effectively zero. Many HIV-positive women in treatment plan pregnancies with the advice of their HIV specialists.
<br> <br>
<strong> 2. During delivery. Infants can be exposed to HIV in the birth canal. The birth process represents the highest level of risk of infection to the baby.</strong>
<br> <br>
    - Again, mothers who are in antiretroviral treatment with suppressed viral levels are highly unlikely to pass the virus on during birth. <br> <br>
    - Mothers who don’t discover their HIV status in time for treatment to suppress their viral levels can greatly reduce the odds of transmission during birth by delivering via caesarian section. <br> <br>
    - Also, certain antiretroviral medications easily pass the placental barrier and offer protection to the baby during birth, even if the mother’s viral level are not yet fully suppressed. It’s important to consult with an HIV medical specialist to determine the best strategies for protection.<br> <br>

<strong> 3. During breastfeeding. Breast milk contains HIV in HIV-positive women who are not in treatment.</strong>
<br> <br>
    - Women who do not begin treatment in time to suppress their viral levels should bottle feed their newborns with formula.<br> <br>
    - The WHO recommends breastfeeding for HIV-positive mothers in antiretroviral treatment with durably undetectable viral load.[1]<br> <br>

In short, antiretroviral treatment can reduce the odds of HIV transmission from mother to child to near zero.[2] Women who are already in effective treatment for HIV when they become pregnant can expect a routine experience with few complications. Women who become infected after pregnancy begins can still greatly reduce if not eliminate the possibility of passing the virus on to their newborns.
<br> <br>
It is very important for expectant mothers and for women who think they may become pregnant to be aware of any risk factors they may have for HIV infection.
<br> <br>
Only testing and treatment can ensure a high likelihood of a good outcome.
<br> <br>
If an expectant mother waits to be tested, it may be too late to prevent HIV transmission to her unborn child.
<br> <br>
Professional medical supervision is critical.
		</p>
