		<h3 class="piece_header"> Queer People Have Mental Health Problems </h3>		
		<p>
		<strong> That proves it’s bad to be queer. Right? </strong> <br> <br>
I write a lot about LGBTQ issues. Tens of thousands of people have read my stories and essays. Thousands of people have taken the time to reply to me and share their views.
<br> <br>
Usually, I hear from queer youth who thank me for inspiring them, or from allies and others who want to share consciousness-raising stories and uplifting tales. Disturbingly, however, I also receive a small but steady stream of bigoted nonsense.
<br> <br>
I hear from people who want to tell me that being queer is wrong. That we’re sinners or that we’re sick. Or both.
<br> <br>
So, check this out.
<br> <br>
A young man recently shared with me that a Catholic priest told him that we LGBTQ people have elevated predispositions to depression, and to learning, mental, and social disabilities. The priest told him that proves that being queer is wrong, that it’s something people must fight against. The kid asked me how he should answer the priest.
<br> <br>
Here’s my response in a nutshell. <br> <br>
<strong> That’s rich. </strong>
<br> <br>
That priest (bless his hoary ole homophobic heart) is simply making a self-fulfilling prophecy.
<br> <br>
Organized religion is largely responsible for oppressing LGBTQ people in the first place. They put the structures in place to cause us to have to hide our true selves, even from our families and other people we love.
<br> <br>
They teach us to be self loathing.
<br> <br>
They dish up the heaping portions of unhealthy homophobia that we internalize.
<br> <br>
They make us scapegoats.
<br> <br>
And then they point fingers and say we have trouble socializing, that we get depressed?
<br> <br>
Well, duh!
<br> <br>
In point of fact, LGBTQ people growing up today have much better chances of being happy, fulfilled and healthy than ever before.
<br> <br>
Why?
<br> <br>
Obviously, because so many of us grow up now understanding that there’s nothing wrong with us, that we’re just ordinary, minority variants of human beings.
<br> <br>
So many of us now have the wonderful opportunity to understand that the priests are full of nonsense. Without that priest and other obnoxious people like him, we’d have very little to worry about.
<br> <br>
Sadly, evil bigots like that priest still have influence. So many of our beautiful young people continue to suffer needlessly, continue to attempt suicide, continue to end up living in shelters or on the street.
<br> <br>
This is what I told my correspondent —
<br> <br>
The next time you see that priest? Tell him you’re onto his game.Tell him to keep quiet and leave decent people alone. Tell him you won’t tolerate his homophobic nonsense.
<br> <br>
Tell him that his barbaric, medieval religious beliefs are gravely harming innocent, intrinsically harmless people. Tell him that the Catholic catechism, which officially teaches school children every day that we queer people are “depraved” and “disordered,” is an evil document.
<br> <br>
Tell him that you insist that he behave like a decent human being instead of an obnoxious bigot.
<br> <br>
Tell him that his beliefs are precisely morally equivalent to those of racists and and anti semites, of members of the Ku Klux Klan, and of Nazi leaders.
<br> <br>
Tell him that he covers himself in shame and disgrace when he speaks out in favor of the stigmatization and dehumanization of his fellow human beings who happen to be biologically different.
<br> <br>
But whatever you do, I said, don’t give his homophobic bigotry a pass. Don’t be silent. Make sure he experiences the social consequences of his evil. Shame him. Shun him.
<br> <br>
Let him know you find him to be repulsive on a deeply personal, visceral level.
<br> <br>
We don’t tolerate racism. We must not tolerate homophobia.
<br> <br>
Religion is no excuse.
<br> <br> <br>
I recently published two serialized stories that explore the harm that queer youth experience due to homophobia. While the characters are fictional, the stories are terribly real, based on experiences that queer youth go through every day.
<br> <br>
If you’d like a peek at the real lives of queer teens who suffer from religious bigotry, please click on the links below.
		</p>
