		<h3 class="piece_header"> Caleb at 18 </h3>		
		<p>
		<strong> After the bad and the good, life goes on </strong> <br> <br>
Dear Amanda, 
<br> <br>

My name is Caleb and I’m gay.
<br> <br>
I know you probably think I can’t know that for real cause I’m only 15. I really know, though.
<br> <br>
Remember that?
<br> <br>
It seems so long ago that you first interviewed me and wrote that down. Probably longer for me than for you.
<br> <br>
Remember how suspicious I was of you?
<br> <br>
I don’t do email so much. I wish you had regular Internet so we could chat, I mean if you wanted to. But that’s OK. Maybe I can take some time and put down some serious thoughts that wouldn’t come to me if we were just talking.
<br> <br>
But anyway, I’m glad you gave me your Gmail, even if you can only check it a few times a week. It must be crazy living down there. I think it’s awesome that you went with Emily to do her research project.
<br> <br>
Are you learning any Mayan, by the way? Is it hard?
<br> <br>
Even though I miss you (a lot!) I am OK. I wanted you to know that. I also want you to know that I might not be OK if it wasn’t for you. My parents are fine, they mostly leave me alone, but I always feel like I have to hide the real Caleb from them.
<br> <br>
Not like with you.
<br> <br>
Remember how you encouraged Travis and Marlene and me to start a Gay Straight Alliance club at school?
<br> <br>
Even though Travis and I just graduated, Marlene will be there next year still, and lots of younger kids are coming to meetings too.
<br> <br>
It’s going strong.
<br> <br>
Thanks to you. You really matter.
<br> <br>
I’m sorry you got fired. I know you said you’d been expecting it, but it really sucks. Don’t those people at CPS get how important you are to some of us?
<br> <br>
You saved my life, Amanda. In so many ways. I don’t know if you’ll every really understand how important you were to me back when I was a confused kid who hated himself.
<br> <br>
You were the first gay adult I ever knew. You were my role model. The only one I had.
<br> <br>
And not just me.
<br> <br>
Marlene still cries about you being gone sometimes. Not to worry you. She’s OK. She’s strong, you know. She’s always been the strongest of all of us.
<br> <br>
Being trans is hard. Super hard. Especially when you’re a kid.
<br> <br>
I still remember how super surprised you were when Travis’s mom offered to take Marlene in. Give her a home. I don’t think much shocks you, but that sure did.
<br> <br>
I think that’s the only time I ever saw you speechless.
<br> <br>
We’re alike in a lot of ways, huh? Kind of sad. We don’t trust people, do we? We’re suspicious and defensive. We’re always ready to fight.
<br> <br>
I guess we have to be, huh? We both learned really young how hard it is to be us.
<br> <br>
Travis never had to learn that, not for real. I’m not saying he doesn’t have his own struggles and challenges, but it’s different for him.
<br> <br>
It’s like we grew up in separate worlds, even though we were only a few blocks apart some of the time, even though our parents were a lot a like in many ways. Except one really important way, obviously.
<br> <br>
Did you know we broke up?
<br> <br>
A little while ago.
<br> <br>
I mean, it was kind of inevitable, anyway. That’s what we told each other. We’re going to be a thousand miles apart at different colleges. We need to be free to live our lives. Right?
<br> <br>
Yeah, but you know what? I don’t know if I can do it. If I can handle a real relationship.
<br> <br>
Travis and I were great, but …
<br> <br>
Amanda, part of me never can get over all the shame I used to feel. Part of me always holds Travis a little bit away from me. Part of me can’t trust him enough to let him all the way in.
<br> <br>
I think he knew that. Knows that. I think that’s why he let me go so easy when I told him.
<br> <br>
I’ll always love Travis. He’ll always be my first, best buddy, and my first kiss. First lots of other things too, but I’ll spare you the details!
<br> <br>
Will it always be like this for me?
<br> <br>
Am I always going to have trouble giving myself all the way to another person?
<br> <br>
How did you manage?
<br> <br>
How did you find Emily and let her in? You’ve hinted a little about how hard it was. I know you were terribly unhappy before you met her.
<br> <br>
I hope I find my Emily one day. I worry that I won’t be able to, but since I have you to look up to, I have hope.
<br> <br>
Thanks so much for being you, even though being you was too much for those asshole bureaucrats where you worked.
<br> <br>
Maybe one day when my kids are my age, if I have kids, it’ll be really, really OK to be like us. Maybe it’ll be so OK that people won’t get fired because they tell abused kids' parents that homophobia is wrong.
<br> <br>
I just can’t get over it. I’m so mad they told you it wasn’t OK to say things like that.
<br> <br>
I haven’t decided yet if I’m going to be a social worker or a lawyer. Whichever I decide, I’m going to do your kind of work.
<br> <br>
I’m going to help people. Our kind of people.
<br> <br>
I just wish I knew if I’m going to be able to help myself.
<br> <br>
I think I can.
<br> <br>
When I doubt, I close my eyes and I see you and Emily’s guardian-spirit rattlesnakes.
<br> <br>
Then for a little while at least, I feel like I can tackle anything.
<br> <br>
Lots of love, Amanda. From Travis and Marlene, but especially from me.
<br> <br>
Your friend always,
<br> <br>
Caleb
<br> <br>
P.S. My dad says hi. He still won’t admit he likes you, but I can tell he really does.
		</p>
